ğŸ§  From MNIST to the Real World
Evaluating and Adapting Digit Recognition Models Beyond the Dataset
ğŸ“Œ Project Overview

This project explores the gap between benchmark datasets and real-world data using handwritten digit recognition as a case study.

A Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is first trained on the classic MNIST dataset and then evaluated on real-world digit images collected manually (paint-drawn and handwritten).
The project demonstrates that high benchmark accuracy does not guarantee real-world robustness, and systematically investigates how preprocessing and fine-tuning can improve performance.

ğŸ¯ Objectives

Train a strong MNIST baseline CNN

Evaluate the model on real-world digit images

Design a robust OpenCV preprocessing pipeline

Quantify performance before and after adaptation

Apply fine-tuning and mixed training

Analyze failure cases and limitations

ğŸ“‚ Datasets
1ï¸âƒ£ MNIST (Benchmark)

60,000 training images

10,000 test images

Grayscale, 28Ã—28 pixels

Digits 0â€“9

2ï¸âƒ£ Real-World Digits (Custom Dataset)

Collected manually and stored in Google Drive:

Paint digits (mouse-drawn, clean background)

Handwritten digits (pen/paper, photographed)

ğŸ“Œ Total images: ~20
ğŸ“Œ Purpose: simulate out-of-distribution (OOD) data

ğŸ§© Methodology

The project is structured into three clear phases.

ğŸ”¹ Phase 1 â€” MNIST Baseline Training
Model

A simple but effective CNN:

2 convolutional blocks (Conv â†’ ReLU â†’ MaxPool)

Fully connected classifier

Dropout for regularization

Training

Optimizer: Adam

Loss: CrossEntropy

Epochs: 10

Normalization using MNIST mean/std

Result

MNIST test accuracy â‰ˆ 99%

Clean convergence, no overfitting

ğŸ“Œ This confirms the model learns the MNIST distribution well.

ğŸ”¹ Phase 2 â€” Real-World Evaluation & Preprocessing
Problem Identified

When applying the MNIST-trained model directly to real images:

Strong performance degradation

High confidence wrong predictions

Especially poor results on handwritten photos

Solution: OpenCV Preprocessing Pipeline

A custom pipeline was designed to convert real images into MNIST-like inputs:

Grayscale conversion

CLAHE contrast normalization

Adaptive / Otsu thresholding

Morphological operations

Contour filtering (reject paper edges & noise)

Centering via center-of-mass

Final 28Ã—28 normalization

Each image is:

Visualized (original vs processed)

Safely processed with failure handling

Logged and exported

ğŸ”¹ Phase 3 â€” Fine-Tuning & Mixed Training
A) Real-World Fine-Tuning

CNN classifier head unfrozen

Convolutional layers frozen

Heavy augmentation on 28Ã—28 digits

Very low learning rate

B) Mixed Fine-Tuning (MNIST + Real-World)

Alternating batches:

MNIST subset

Real-world digits

All layers unfrozen

Extremely low learning rate

Prevents catastrophic forgetting

ğŸ“Š Results & Analysis
Real-World Accuracy (Summary)
Stage	Overall	Paint	Handwritten
Before adaptation	~0.42	~0.60	~0.22
After fine-tuning	~0.47	~0.60	~0.33
Mixed fine-tuning	~0.47	~0.60	~0.33

ğŸ“ˆ A bar chart comparing paint vs handwritten across stages is included in the project.

ğŸ” Key Observations

Paint digits are relatively easy and already close to MNIST

Handwritten photos are the true challenge

Preprocessing is more important than model complexity

Fine-tuning improves robustness but is limited by data scarcity

The model often makes confident mistakes on OOD inputs

ğŸ“Œ This mirrors real industrial ML behavior.

âš ï¸ Limitations

Extremely small real-world dataset (~20 images)

No domain-specific data augmentation beyond geometry/noise

CNN architecture intentionally simple

No test-time augmentation or ensemble methods

